{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20150102184338|640686619","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Ron_Barber","to":"Ron Barber"}],"pages":{"30391312":{"pageid":30391312,"ns":0,"title":"Ron Barber","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2015-01-02T18:45:25Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n|name         = Ron Barber\n|image        = Rob barber, Official Portrait, 112th Congress.jpg\n|state        = [[Arizona]]\n|district     = {{ushr|Arizona|2|2nd}}\n|term_start   = January 3, 2013\n|term_end     = <!-- January 3, 2015 -->\n|predecessor  = [[Trent Franks]]\n|successor    = [[Martha McSally]] {{small|(Elect)}}\n|state1       = [[Arizona]]\n|district1    = {{ushr|Arizona|8|8th}}\n|term_start1  = June 12, 2012\n|term_end1    = January 3, 2013\n|predecessor1 = [[Gabrielle Giffords]]\n|successor1   = [[Trent Franks]]\n|birth_name   = Ronald Sylvester Barber\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1945|8|25}}\n|birth_place  = [[Wakefield]], [[United Kingdom]]\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse       = Nancy Barber\n|children     = Jenny<br>Crissi\n|alma_mater   = [[University of Arizona]]\n|religion     = [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholicism]]\n|website      = [http://maffei.house.gov House website]\n}}\n'''Ronald Sylvester \"Ron\" Barber''' (born August 25, 1945) is an [[United States|American]] politician who has been a member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] since 2012. Barber, a member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] from [[Arizona]], served as district director for U.S. Representative [[Gabrielle Giffords]] before Giffords resigned her seat due to the severe injuries she sustained in an [[2011 Tucson shooting|assassination attempt]], in which Barber was also injured. He won the Democratic nomination for the special election to finish Giffords's term<ref name=specialelectionwin>{{cite news|title=Former Gabrielle Giffords aide Ron Barber wins election to finish her term|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-250_162-57452078/former-gabrielle-giffords-aide-ron-barber-wins-election-to-finish-her-term|accessdate=June 13, 2012|publisher=[[CBS News]]|date=June 13, 2012}}</ref> and was sworn into office on June 19, 2012.<ref name=specialelectionwin/>\n\nIn the 2012 general election, he was elected to a full term. His district&mdash;numbered as the [[Arizona's 8th congressional district|8th district]] in 2012, and as the [[Arizona's 2nd congressional district|2nd district]] since 2013&mdash;includes the eastern two-thirds of [[Tucson, Arizona|Tucson]], as well as the southeastern corner of Arizona. Barber lost his [[United States House of Representatives elections in Arizona, 2014#District 2|2014 re-election]] bid to [[Martha McSally]] by 167 votes. <ref>{{cite news|last1=Cahn|first1=Emily|title=McSally Win Gives Republicans Another House Seat|url=http://atr.rollcall.com/elections-2014-ron-barber-martha-mcsally-results/?dcz=|accessdate=17 December 2014|work=Roll Call|date=17 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBarber was born in [[Wakefield]], [[England]], shortly after [[World War II]].<ref>[http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/us-politics/9322762/The-British-born-Democrat-Ron-Barber-aiming-to-replace-Gabrielle-Giffords-in-Arizona.html \"Ron Barber aiming to replace Gabrielle Giffords in Arizona\"], telegraph.co.uk; accessed November 15, 2014.</ref> His father was an airman stationed at [[Davis-Monthan Air Force Base]]. Barber graduated from Tucson's [[Rincon High School]] in  1963, and earned a B.A. from the [[University of Arizona]] in 1967.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=B001279|title=Barber, Ron|date= June 20, 2012|publisher=[[Biographical Directory of the United States Congress]]|location=[[Washington, D.C.]]|accessdate=June 23, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Early public sector career==\nBarber worked as director and program manager of the Arizona Division of Developmental Disabilities in [[Pima County, Arizona|Pima County]] from 1974 to 2006.<ref name=\"campaignbio\">[http://ronbarberforcongress.com/meet-ron/ Campaign Biography]</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Sanders|first=Rebekah L.|title=Election for Giffords' seat a mercurial race|url=http://www.azcentral.com/news/politics/articles/2012/04/14/20120414giffords-seat-race.html|accessdate=June 13, 2012|newspaper=[[Arizona Republic]]|date=April 14, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Neighbor|first=Megan|title=Arizona shooting: Staffer displayed his devotion to Gabrielle Giffords|url=http://www.azcentral.com/news/articles/2011/01/12/20110112gabrielle-giffords-arizona-shooting-survivor-ron-barber.html|accessdate=June 13, 2012|newspaper=[[Arizona Republic]]|date=January 12, 2011}}</ref>\n\nBarber worked as Giffords' district director beginning in 2007. On January 8, 2011, Barber was shot in the thigh and face during an [[2011 Tucson shooting|attempt on Giffords' life]], in which Giffords was badly injured and six people were killed.\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n;2012 special election\n{{Main|Arizona's 8th congressional district special election, 2012}}\nIn 2012, following the resignation of Giffords, Barber decided to seek election to the seat. On June 12, 2012, he defeated Jesse Kelly, an [[Iraq War]] veteran, in a [[special election]].<ref name=specialelectionwin/><ref name=swearingin1>{{cite news|last=Myers|first=Amanda Lee|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|title=Jesse Kelly 'Reflecting' After Losing To Ron Barber In Race To Replace Gabrielle Giffords|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/06/13/jesse-kelly-ron-barber-gabrielle-giffords-az-special-election-results_n_1594750.html|accessdate=June 14, 2012|publisher=The Huffington Post|date=June 13, 2012}}</ref><ref>[http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5gxb-URnnsq8p1UTqiR7VnCQ7DBjQ?docId=CNG.3ff6b80e76f3a531701730d791b3fa9f.361 \"Barber sworn-in to succeed Gabby Giffords.\"], Google News. June 19, 2012.</ref>\n\n;2012 regular election\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Arizona, 2012#District 2}}\nOn March 19, 2012, Barber announced that he would run for a full term in the district, which had been renumbered as the 2nd District, in the 2012 general election.<ref name=\"campaignbio\"/> The district was, at least on paper, slightly more Democratic than its predecessor.<ref name=nj>{{cite web|url=http://hotlineoncall.nationaljournal.com/archives/2011/10/house-democrats.php|title=House Democrats Gain With New Arizona Map|date=October 5, 2011|accessdate=October 7, 2011|work=[[National Journal]]|first=Jessica|last=Taylor}}</ref> However, his race against Republican [[Martha McSally]] was one of the closest in the nation. McSally led on election night by a few hundred votes, but the race was initially too close to call due to a large number of provisional ballots. Barber eventually overtook McSally as more ballots were counted. By November 16, most of the outstanding ballots were in heavily Democratic precincts near Tucson. ''[[The Arizona Republic]]'' determined that as a result, McSally would not be able to pick up enough votes to overcome Barber's lead.<ref name=ArizonaRepublic>Nowicki, Dan; D'Anna, Jon. [http://www.azcentral.com/news/politics/articles/20121116barber-wins-race-mcsally-arizona-district-2.html Barber wins hard-fought race against McSally]. [[The Arizona Republic]], November 17, 2012.</ref> By November 17, Barber's lead over McSally had grown to 1,400 votes. The same day, the [[Associated Press]] determined that there weren't enough ballots outstanding for McSally to regain the lead, and called the race for Barber.<ref>[http://www.tucsonnewsnow.com/story/20125699/ap \"Voters in Arizona's 2nd pick Barber over McSally.\"], [[Associated Press]] via [[KOLD-TV]], November 17, 2012.</ref> McSally conceded the race later that morning.<ref name=ArizonaRepublic/>\n\n;2014\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Arizona, 2014#District 2}}\nBarber is running for re-election in 2014. The Democratic primary election took place on August 26, 2014, with the general election slated for November 4, 2014. [[Martha McSally]], whom Barber defeated in the 2012 election, won the Republican primary.<ref>{{cite web|title=Arizona's 2nd Congressional District elections, 2014|url=http://web1.ballotpedia.org/Arizona%27s_2nd_Congressional_District_elections,_2014|publisher=Ballotpedia|accessdate=March 19, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=McSally pilots easy Arizona GOP primary win to face Democratic Rep. Barber in rematch|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2014/08/27/mcsally-pilots-easy-arizona-gop-primary-win-to-face-democratic-rep-barber-in|accessdate=August 28, 2014|publisher=Fox News|date=2014-08-27}}</ref> According to ''[[USA Today]]'', Arizona's 2nd Congressional District will feature one of the most competitive House races of 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last=Schouten|first=Fredreka|title=Latino group to run ads hitting Arizona Democrat over Obamacare|url=http://onpolitics.usatoday.com/2014/03/14/ron-barber-obamacare-affordable-care-act-latinos|accessdate=March 19, 2014|newspaper=USA Today|date=March 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2014, [[Americans for Responsible Solutions]], a pro-gun control PAC founded by Gabby Giffords, began running television ads in support of Barber.<ref name=solutions>{{cite news|last1=Isenstadt|first1=Alex|title=Gabrielle Giffords\u2019 ad push aims to aid successor|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2014/09/arizona-ads-giffords-gun-control-110529.html|accessdate=September 10, 2014|publisher=Politico|date=9-3-2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Miller|first1=S.A.|title=Giffords' gun control group runs ad to boost Barber|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2014/sep/7/gabby-giffords-gun-control-group-runs-ad-to-boost-|accessdate=September 10, 2014|publisher=Washington Times|date=September 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nWith 100% of the votes counted, McSally had a 161 vote lead and declared victory on November 12, 2014, but due to the fact that the margin of victory was less than 1%, an automatic recount is legally required in Arizona. Barber's campaign has been holding on to hope that 762 rejected ballots from Pima County will be counted during the recount, which began on December 3, 2014.<ref name=\"jrn.com\">[http://www.jrn.com/kgun9/news/Recount-next-in-Barber-McSally-race-282507511.html Recount in Barber-McSally race due to 161 margin of victory for McSally], jrn.com; accessed November 14, 2014.</ref><ref>[http://tucson.com/news/local/recount-starts-today-in-mcsally-vs-barber-race/article_c8a326c4-fd49-5469-8eee-c67ece92e3e4.html Recount starts today in McSally vs. Barber race], [[Arizona Daily Star]], December 3, 2014. Retrieved 8 December 2014.</ref>\n\nUltimately, Barber lost the recount to McSally by 167 votes. <ref>{{cite news|last1=Cahn|first1=Emily|title=McSally Win Gives Republicans Another House Seat|url=http://atr.rollcall.com/elections-2014-ron-barber-martha-mcsally-results/?dcz=|accessdate=17 December 2014|work=Roll Call|date=17 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nTouting his independence, Barber has voted the same way as [[Speaker of the House]] [[John Boehner]] on 10 out of the 16 occasions that Boehner has chosen to cast a vote - more than any other House Democrat.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-10-29/some-democrats-vote-with-boehner-touting-independence.html|title=Some Democrats Vote With Boehner Touting Independence|last=Giroux|first=Greg|date=October 28, 2013|work=Bloomberg|accessdate=November 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\n;Health care policy\nIn May 2013, Barber voted against repeal of the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424127887324767004578489291287632114.html|title=Obamacare and Vulnerable Democrats|date=May 20, 2013|publisher=The Wall Street Journal}}</ref>\n\n;Gun control\nBarber is a strong supporter of gun control laws.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lachman|first=Samantha|title=Martha McSally's Bid To Flip Arizona Dem Ron Barber's House Seat Just Got A Bit Easier|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/01/13/ron-barber-martha-mcsally_n_4590432.html|accessdate=March 19, 2014|newspaper=Huffington Post|date=January 13, 2014}}</ref> In 2013, Barber co-sponsored a bill that would expand background checks on gun sales.<ref name=solutions/>\n\n;Abortion\nBarber characterizes himself as pro-choice, and has voted against legislation that would prohibit federal funding for health plans that include abortion services.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ron Barber's Voting Records on Issue: Abortion|url=https://votesmart.org/candidate/key-votes/137292/ron-barber/2/abortion#.UzSPi14wlUE|publisher=Project Vote Smart|accessdate=March 27, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=On Passage: H R 7 To prohibit taxpayer funded abortions|url=http://www.opencongress.org/vote/2014/h/30|work=Open Congress|publisher=Sunlight Foundation|accessdate=March 27, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=House Vote 29 - H.R.7: On Motion to Recommit with Instructions|url=https://politics.nytimes.com/congress/votes/113/house/2/29|accessdate=March 27, 2014|newspaper=New York Times}}</ref>\n\n;Gay rights\nBarber is a co-sponsor of the [[Respect for Marriage Act]].<ref name=Questionnaire>{{cite web|title=Phoenix Arizona Election Questionnaire for Congress, RON BARBER|url=http://www.azcentral.com/news/politics/2012questionnaires/results.php?id=barberr|publisher=Gannett|accessdate=25 April 2014}}</ref> He supported the repeal of [[Don't Ask, Don't Tell Repeal Act of 2010|Don't Ask, Don't Tell]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Nintzel|first=Jim|title=CD 8 candidates Ron Barber and Jesse Kelly split on abortion, gay rights|url=http://www.tucsonweekly.com/tucson/social-study/Content?oid=3411327|accessdate=March 19, 2014|newspaper=Tucson Weekly|date=May 31, 2012}}</ref>\n\n;Immigration\nBarber has called for increased border security. He supports the \"[[DREAM Act]]\".<ref name=Questionnaire />\n\n===Committee assignments===\nBarber served on these committees.<ref>[http://barber.house.gov/press-release/us-rep-ron-barber-appointed-house-armed-services-committee U.S. Rep. Ron Barber Appointed to House Armed Services Committee]</ref>\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Armed Services|Committee on Armed Services]]'''\n**[[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Tactical Air and Land Forces|Subcommittee on Tactical Air and Land Forces]]\n**[[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Readiness|Subcommittee on Readiness]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Homeland Security|Committee on Homeland Security]]'''\n**[[United States House Homeland Security Subcommittee on Oversight and Management Efficiency|Subcommittee on Oversight and Management Efficiency]] (Ranking member)\n\n==Personal life==\nRon Barber and his wife Nancy live in [[Tucson, Arizona]]; the couple has two daughters. The Barbers operate a small business.<ref>[http://blog.advocatesaz.org/2012/05/16/special-election-on-june-12-ron-barber-stands-with-planned-parenthood Special Election on June 12: Ron Barber Stands with Planned Parenthood], blog.advocatesaz.org, May 16, 2012.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{bioguide}}\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n* [http://barber.house.gov/ Congressman Ron Barber] official U.S. House site\n* [http://ronbarberforcongress.com/ Ron Barber for Congress] \n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Arizona/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Ron_Barber_%5BD-2%5D}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio= B001279 | ballot = Ron_Barber | nndb = 928/000356857 | votesmart = 137292 | govtrack = 412502 | natjournal = 3493 | opencong = 412502 | rollcall = 44235 | politifact = | fec = H2AZ08094 | opensecrets = N00033981 | assets = | legistorm = 2868/Rep_Ron_Barber.html | followthemoney = | ontheissues = House/Ron_Barber.htm | congress = ron-barber/2093 | worldcat = | c-span = ronbarber | rose = | imdb = 5098245 | bloomberg = | nyt = b/ron_barber | wsj = | washpo = 5e8059b2-747b-11e2-95e4-6148e45d7adb }}\n*{{ballotpedia|Ron_Barber}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Gabrielle Giffords]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Arizona|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Arizona's 8th congressional district]]|years=2012\u20132013}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Trent Franks]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Trent Franks]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Arizona|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Arizona's 2nd congressional district]]|years=2013\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Martha McSally]]<br>{{small|Elect}}}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Suzanne Bonamici]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=347th}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Suzan DelBene]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{AZ-FedRep}}\n{{USCongRep-start|congresses= 112th\u2013113th [[United States Congress]]es |state=[[Arizona]]}}\n{{USCongRep/AZ/112}}\n{{USCongRep/AZ/113}}\n{{USCongRep-end}}\n{{USHouseCurrent}}\n\n{{Persondata\n| NAME              = Barber, Ron\n| ALTERNATIVE NAMES = Barber, Ronald Sylvester\n| SHORT DESCRIPTION = U.S. House of Representatives (D-AZ)  \n| DATE OF BIRTH     = August 25, 1945\n| PLACE OF BIRTH    = Wakefield, West Yorkshire, England, UK \n| DAT